# CHAPTER XII.

The Brâhma*n*a said:

I have crossed beyond that very impassable place, in which fancies are
the gadflies and mosquitoes <span id="fr_1368"></span>[3](#fn_1363.md), in
which grief and joy are cold and heat, in which delusion is the blinding
darkness, in which avarice is the beasts of prey and reptiles, in which
desire and anger are the obstructors, the way to which consists in
worldly objects, and is to be crossed by one singly <span
id="fr_1369"></span>[4](#fn_1364.md). And I have entered the great
forest <span id="fr_1370"></span>[5](#fn_1365.md).

The Brâhma*n*a's wife said:

Where is that forest, O very intelligent person! what are the trees
(there), and what the rivers, and the hills and mountains; and at what
distance is that forest?

<span id="page_285">p. 285</span>

The Brâhma*n*a said:

There is nothing else more delightful than that, when there is no
distinction from it. There is nothing more afflicting than that, when
there is a distinction from it <span id="fr_1371"></span>[1](#fn_1366.md).
There is nothing smaller than that, there is nothing larger than
that <span id="fr_1372"></span>[2](#fn_1367.md). There is nothing more
subtle than that; there is no other happiness equal to, that. Entering
it, the twice-born do not grieve, and do not exult <span
id="fr_1373"></span>[3](#fn_1368.md). They are not afraid of anybody, and
nobody is afraid of them. In that forest <span
id="fr_1374"></span>[4](#fn_1369.md) are seven large trees <span
id="fr_1375"></span>[5](#fn_1370.md), seven fruits, and seven guests; seven
hermitages, seven (forms of) concentration, and seven (forms of)
initiation. This is the description of the forest. That forest is filled
with trees producing splendid flowers and fruits of five colours <span
id="fr_1376"></span>[6](#fn_1371.md). That forest

<span id="page_286">p. 286</span>

is filled with trees producing flowers and fruits of four colours. That
forest is filled with trees producing flowers and fruits of three
colours, and mixed. That forest is filled with trees producing flowers
and fruits of two colours, and of beautiful colours. That forest is
filled with trees producing flowers and fruits of one colour, and
fragrant. That forest is filled with two large trees producing numerous
flowers and fruits of undistinguished colours <span
id="fr_1377"></span>[1](#fn_1372.md). There is one fire <span
id="fr_1378"></span>[2](#fn_1373.md) here, connected with the Brahman <span
id="fr_1379"></span>[3](#fn_1374.md), and having a good mind <span
id="fr_1380"></span>[4](#fn_1375). And there is fuel here, (namely.md) the
five senses. The seven (forms of) emancipation from them are the seven
(forms of) initiation <span id="fr_1381"></span>[5](#fn_1376.md). The
qualities are the fruits, and the guests eat the fruits. There, in
various places, the great sages receive hospitality. And when they have
been worshipped and have disappeared <span
id="fr_1382"></span>[6](#fn_1377.md), another forest shines forth, in which
intelligence is the tree, and emancipation the fruit, and which
possesses shade (in the form of) tranquillity,

<span id="page_287">p. 287</span>

which depends on knowledge, which has contentment for its water, and
which has the Kshetra*g*ña within for the sun. The good who attain to
that, have no fear afterwards. Its end cannot be perceived upwards or
downwards or horizontally <span id="fr_1383"></span>[1](#fn_1378.md). There
always dwell seven females there <span
id="fr_1384"></span>[2](#fn_1379), with faces (turned.md) downwards, full
of brilliance, and causes of generation. They absorb <span
id="fr_1385"></span>[3](#fn_1380.md) all the higher delights of people, as
inconstancy (absorbs) everything <span
id="fr_1386"></span>[4](#fn_1381.md). In that same <span
id="fr_1387"></span>[5](#fn_1382) (principle.md) the seven perfect sages,
together with their chiefs, the richest <span
id="fr_1388"></span>[6](#fn_1383.md), abide, and again emerge from the
same. Glory; brilliance, and greatness, enlightenment, victory,
perfection, and power <span id="fr_1389"></span>[7](#fn_1384.md)--these
seven rays follow after this same sun. Hills and mountains also are
there collected together, and rivers and streams flowing with water
produced from the Brahman <span id="fr_1390"></span>[8](#fn_1385.md). And
there is the confluence of the rivers in the secluded place <span
id="fr_1391"></span>[9](#fn_1386.md) for the

<span id="page_288">p. 288</span>

sacrifice, whence those who are contented in their own selfs repair to
the divine grandsire himself. Those whose wishes are reduced <span
id="fr_1392"></span>[1](sbe0840.htm#fn_1387), whose wishes are (fixed.md)
on good vows, whose sins are burnt up by penance, merging the self in
the self <span id="fr_1393"></span>[2](sbe0840.htm#fn_1388.md), devote
themselves to Brahman. Those people who understand the forest of
knowledge <span id="fr_1394"></span>[3](sbe0840.htm#fn_1389.md), praise
tranquillity. And aspiring to that forest, they are born so as not to
lose courage <span id="fr_1395"></span>[4](sbe0840.htm#fn_1390.md). Such,
indeed, is this holy forest, as understood by Brâhma*n*as. And
understanding it, they act (accordingly), being directed by the
Kshetra*g*ña.

