### Footnotes

<span id="fn_1361"></span>[284:1](sbe0838.htm#fr_1366.md) Cf. Gîtâ, [p.
61](sbe0806.htm#page_61.md). The water is that required for the sacrifice.
The words 'the Brahman is his origin' are not quite clear, as being not
connected with the figure employed. Perhaps it might be taken otherwise
thus, 'the Brahman (is) the fire produced from the Brahman,' this last
standing for the ara*n*i.

<span id="fn_1362"></span>[284:2](sbe0838.htm#fr_1367.md) I. e. one who
understands the truth, Nîlaka*nth*a; God, Ar*g*una Mi*s*ra. The same
sentence winds up two of the following chapters; and at [p.
310](sbe0846.htm#page_310.md) K*ri*sh*n*a says the Kshetra*g*ña signifies
the supreme self. See Gîtâ, [p. 102](sbe0814.htm#page_102.md) seq.

<span id="fn_1363"></span>[284:3](sbe0839.htm#fr_1368.md) Cf. Lalita
Vistara, p. 44.

<span id="fn_1364"></span>[284:4](sbe0839.htm#fr_1369.md) I. e. not with
the help of son, wealth, &c., says Nîlaka*nth*a, as each man's salvation
after having got into the course of worldly life depends on himself. Cf.
*S*ânti Parvan (Moksha Dharma), chap. 193, st. 32, and Manu IV, 240;
obstructor, thief, Ar*g*una Mi*s*ra.

<span id="fn_1365"></span>[284:5](sbe0839.htm#fr_1370.md) I. e. the
Brahman. Nîlaka*nth*a compares a text from the *S*ruti, 'Kim svid
vana*m* ka u sa v*ri*ksha âsa;' see Rig-veda X, 31, 7.

<span id="fn_1366"></span>[285:1](sbe0839.htm#fr_1371.md) Cf. *Kh*ândogya,
pp. 516, 517.

<span id="fn_1367"></span>[285:2](sbe0839.htm#fr_1372.md) Cf.
Sanatsu*g*âtîya, [p. 180](sbe0825.htm#page_180.md) and note there.

<span id="fn_1368"></span>[285:3](sbe0839.htm#fr_1373.md) Cf. as to all
this Gîtâ, [p. 101](sbe0814.htm#page_101.md).

<span id="fn_1369"></span>[285:4](sbe0839.htm#fr_1374.md) This is not the
forest spoken of before. but what has been before called the 'impassable
place,' but which also at [p. 286](#page_286.md) is by implication called a
forest, viz. the course of worldly life.

<span id="fn_1370"></span>[285:5](sbe0839.htm#fr_1375.md) Viz. the eye,
ear, tongue, skin, and nose, and the mind, and understanding--these are
called trees, as being producers of the fruits, namely, the pleasures
and pains derived from their several operations; the guests are the
powers of each sense personified--they receive the fruits above
described; the hermitages are the trees above mentioned, in which the
guests take shelter; the seven forms of concentration are the exclusion
from the self of the seven functions of the seven senses &c. already
referred to; the seven forms of initiation refer to the initiation into
the higher life, by repudiating as not one's own the actions of each
member out of the group of seven. Cf. as to this *Kh*ândogya, p. 219,
and commentary there.

<span id="fn_1371"></span>[285:6](sbe0839.htm#fr_1376.md) Cf. for these
different numbers of colours, Yoga-sûtra II, 19, and commentary, p. 105,
and *S*â<u>n</u>khya-sâra, p. 18. The trees here meant are the
Tanmâtras, or subtle elements, and the theory is that the
Gandha-tanmâtra, or subtle element of smell, has five qualities, its
<span id="page_286">p. 286</span> own special one, so to say, and the
four special ones of the others; the next is taste, the next colour, the
next touch, and the last sound; each has one quality less than its
predecessor. See Yoga-sûtra, p. 106, and gloss; *S*â<u>n</u>khya-sûtra
I, 62; and Vedânta Paribhâshâ, p. 45.

<span id="fn_1372"></span>[286:1](sbe0839.htm#fr_1377.md) These are mind
and understanding; the fruits and flowers are here of 'undistinguished
colours,' as the text expresses it, since they include the colours of
all the fruits of all the other five sets of trees; that is to say, the
subject-matter of their operations is sound, taste, &c., the
subject-matters of all the senses together. 'Undistinguished colours'
is, perhaps, more literally 'of colours not clear.' Ar*g*una Mi*s*ra
paraphrases it by 'of variegated colours,' which is no doubt the true
ultimate sense.

<span id="fn_1373"></span>[286:2](sbe0839.htm#fr_1378.md) The self,
Nîlaka*nth*a. See [p. 279](sbe0837.htm#page_279.md), note
 [7](sbe0837.htm#fn_1336.md) supra.

<span id="fn_1374"></span>[286:3](sbe0839.htm#fr_1379.md) I. e., I presume,
devoted to the Brahman.

<span id="fn_1375"></span>[286:4](sbe0839.htm#fr_1380.md) I. e. true
knowledge, Ar*g*una Mi*s*ra.

<span id="fn_1376"></span>[286:5](sbe0839.htm#fr_1381.md) See note
 [5](#fn_1370), [p. 285](#page_285.md).

<span id="fn_1377"></span>[286:6](sbe0839.htm#fr_1382.md) I. e. when the
senses having worked, as unconnected with the self, are finally absorbed
into it. Cf. *S*â<u>n</u>khya-kârikâ 49 and Ka*th*a, p. 151.

<span id="fn_1378"></span>[287:1](sbe0839.htm#fr_1383.md) It extends on all
sides, its end cannot be perceived on any side.

<span id="fn_1379"></span>[287:2](sbe0839.htm#fr_1384.md) These are,
according to Ar*g*una Mi*s*ra, the Mahat, Aha<u>n</u>kâra, and five
Tanmâtras. Their faces are turned downwards, as they are obstacles in
the way upwards, viz. the way of final emancipation; they are brilliant,
as they light up the course of worldly life; and hence, too, they are
'causes of generation.' They give birth to the universe.

<span id="fn_1380"></span>[287:3](sbe0839.htm#fr_1385.md) They conceal the
higher delight of final emancipation.

<span id="fn_1381"></span>[287:4](sbe0839.htm#fr_1386.md) I follow Ar*g*una
Mi*s*ra, but the text is doubtful.

<span id="fn_1382"></span>[287:5](sbe0839.htm#fr_1387.md) Viz. the Brahman.

<span id="fn_1383"></span>[287:6](sbe0839.htm#fr_1388.md) Cf. *Kh*ândogya,
pp. 295-300. The word sages here, as before, means the various organs.
See B*ri*hadâra*n*yaka, p. 415.

<span id="fn_1384"></span>[287:7](sbe0839.htm#fr_1389.md) Glory = renown;
brilliance = Brahmic splendour (Brahmate*g*as); perfection = obtaining
what is desired; power = not being conquered by others, Ar*g*una
Mi*s*ra. About the sun, see line 3 of text above.

<span id="fn_1385"></span>[287:8](sbe0839.htm#fr_1390.md) I. e.
contentment. See the second line in the text above.

<span id="fn_1386"></span>[287:9](sbe0839.htm#fr_1391.md) I. e. the space
in the heart, the sacrifice being that of 'concentration of mind,'
yogaya*g*ña,--Nîlaka*nth*a. A confluence of rivers is very sacred--here
the meaning intended seems to be the absorption of all desires by
contentment into the heart.

